1) Install and load libraries in R

In R, libraries (also called packages) are collections of pre-written code that extend the functionality of the base R language. They contain functions, datasets, and documentation that you can use to simplify your tasks, enhance your analyses, or add new capabilities to R. (similar to modules in Python)

There are two main functions to grasp here.

  1. install.packages("libraryname"): allows us to download a library if we have not done so previously

  2. load("libraryname"): allows us to load the library, enables us to use its functionality

Note: You do not have to repeatedly install a library. Once you have downloaded a library, it will be accessible to you the next time you launch R, provided that you load the library.

Note When installing a library, you need to put wrap the library name in quotations.

# note: if library not installed yet, you will receive an error 
# when you run the following line without the hash
# library("nycflights13") 

# to install a library
install.packages('nycflights13')

# to load a library
library('nycflights13')


# following line allows us to install and load a library (nycflights13) if it's not on R
# if library is in R, it will load the library immediately
if (!require('nycflights13')) install.packages('nycflights13'); library('nycflights13')

Brief discussion on nycflights13

nycflights13 is a library consisting of 5 different data frames. It provides information about flights departing from New York City (NYC) airports in 2013.

To explore the contents in a library, you will need to load the library first.

Then, you can try typing libraryname:: on your console e.g. nycflights13::

Remember, always load(libraryname) before use.

2) Intro to dplyr

dplyr is a library that provides a set of functions for data manipulation. It is part of a collection of R packages designed for data science.

Common data manipulation operations include:

  1. select - select columns/variables

  2. filter - select rows/observations

  3. mutate - add columns/variables

  4. arrange - re-order observations

  5. summarise - reduce info to a single row

  6. group_by - aggregate different

  7. left_join - merge different data objects

  8. distinct - remove duplicate entries

There are two ways to use dplyr.

  1. Using the Pipe Operator (%>%):

    The pipe operator (%>%) is a core features of dplyr, and it allows us to chain multiple operations together in a left-to-right sequence. This makes the code more readable by eliminating the need for nested functions and ensuring that each operation is performed step-by-step.

    Example: new_data <- data %>% verb1(options) %>% verb2(options) %>% verb3(options)

    How it works: The pipe operator takes the output of the expression on its left and “pipes” it into the next function on its right. Each verb (verb1, verb2, verb3, etc.) is applied sequentially to the data.

  2. Using Each Verb as a Function:

    Alternatively, you can use each dplyr verb as a standalone function, one after the other. In this case, you’ll typically nest the functions. Just like in mathematics, when dealing with composite functions, R processes the innermost function first.

    Example: new_data <- verb3(verb2(verb1(data, options1), options2), options3)

    How it works: The operations are nested inside each other. R will first evaluate the innermost function (verb1()), then apply verb2() to the result, and then finally apply verb3() to the outcome.

Template for dplyr verbs

# to install and load dplyr
if (!require('dplyr')) install.packages('dplyr'); library('dplyr')

# method 1: Chaining operations with %>%
'new_data <- data %>%
  verb1(options) %>%     # First verb/operation
  verb2(options) %>%     # Second verb/operation
  verb3(options)         # Third verb/operation
'

# method 2: Using verbs as nested functions
' new_data <- verb3(verb2(verb1(data, options1), options2), options3)
'

Selecting specific columns

select() allows us to choose specific columns from a data frame

library(dplyr)
library(nycflights13)
airports<-airports
flights<-flights

# when using dplyr, we can refer to the column names freely, without 
# using attach() from base R.

# select() – Select Columns/Variables
# to choose specific columns or variables from a data frame or tibble.

# Example:
# Select faa and name columns from the airportdata
# using pipe operator
df <- flights %>% select(1:3, dep_delay,arr_delay,carrier)

# using verbs as a function
df_verb<-select(flights,1:3, dep_delay,arr_delay,carrier)
head(df_verb,n=3)
## # A tibble: 3 × 6
##    year month   day dep_delay arr_delay carrier
##   <int> <int> <int>     <dbl>     <dbl> <chr>  
## 1  2013     1     1         2        11 UA     
## 2  2013     1     1         4        20 UA     
## 3  2013     1     1         2        33 AA

Additional options for select()

We can include the following options in select() to allow us to select specific columns.

  • starts_with(): Select columns that start with a character string
  • ends_with(): Select columns that end with a character string
  • contains(): Select columns that contain a character string
  • matches(): Select columns that match a regular expression
library(nycflights13)
flights<-flights
df <- flights %>% select(1:3, dep_delay,arr_delay,carrier)

# starts_with
df_select_d<-df%>% select(starts_with("d"))

# ends_with
df_select_delay<-df%>% select(ends_with("delay"))

# contains
df_contain_delay<-df%>% select(contains("delay"))

# matches
df_matches_day<-df%>% select(matches("day"))

# more examples
df_contain_delay<-df%>% select(day,contains("delay"),starts_with("carrier"))

# we can use matches() to select multiple columns
# here, I am selecting columns that have either "dep" or "arr" in the column name.
df_contain_delay<-df%>% select(matches("dep|arr"))

Additional concept to to omit a few columns instead of just omitting one column

# we can use column number or column name when selecting

Filtering

filter() allows us to filter rows based on conditions. We are able to filter numerical and categorical data.

# filter() – Select Rows/Observations
# to filter rows based on conditions

# Example:
# Filter rows where dep_delay is greater than 0
# using pipe operator
df_filtered <- df %>% filter(dep_delay > 0)

# using verbs as a function
df_filtered_verb<-filter(df,dep_delay > 0)

head(df_filtered,n=3)
## # A tibble: 3 × 6
##    year month   day dep_delay arr_delay carrier
##   <int> <int> <int>     <dbl>     <dbl> <chr>  
## 1  2013     1     1         2        11 UA     
## 2  2013     1     1         4        20 UA     
## 3  2013     1     1         2        33 AA
# Further example where we are filtering a categorical variable/column
# filtering rows with faa values ALB, BDL and BTV
# ALB, BDL and BTV are texts/strings. so we need quotations. 
# c() is a function to concatenate them together

# using pipe operator
airports_filtered_pipe<-airports %>% filter(faa %in% c('ALB','BDL','BTV')) 

# using verbs as a function
airports_filtered_verb<-airports %>% filter(faa %in% c('ALB','BDL','BTV'))
head(airports_filtered_verb,n=3)
## # A tibble: 3 × 8
##   faa   name              lat   lon   alt    tz dst   tzone           
##   <chr> <chr>           <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <chr> <chr>           
## 1 ALB   Albany Intl      42.7 -73.8   285    -5 A     America/New_York
## 2 BDL   Bradley Intl     41.9 -72.7   173    -5 A     America/New_York
## 3 BTV   Burlington Intl  44.5 -73.2   335    -5 A     America/New_York

Note: Usage of %in%

When checking if a particular phrase is in a vector, the syntax to use is phrase %in% vector, not vector %in% phrase.

When we are filtering rows that contain a specific term, the syntax is df %>% filter(column %in% specific terms), not df %>% filter(specific terms %in% column)

Mutating (Transforming columns)

mutate() allows us to create new columns or modify existing columns

# mutate() – Add Columns/Variables
# to create new columns or modify existing ones.

# Example:
# Calculate total delay
# using pipe operator
df_filtered <- df_filtered %>% mutate(total_delay = dep_delay+arr_delay)
# using verbs as a function
df_filtered_verb<-mutate(df_filtered,total_delay = dep_delay+arr_delay)

head(df_filtered,n=3)
## # A tibble: 3 × 7
##    year month   day dep_delay arr_delay carrier total_delay

## 2  2013     1     1         4        20 UA               24
## 3  2013     1     1         2        33 AA               35

Arranging

arrange() allows us to sort data frame according to specified columns. The default sorts in ascending order. To sort in descending order, include desc().

# arrange() – Re-order Observations
# to reorder rows based on one or more variables. 
# By default, it sorts in ascending order, 
# but you can use the desc() function for descending order.

# Example:
# Arrange rows by tot_delay in descending order
# using pipe operator
df_filtered <- df_filtered %>% arrange(desc(total_delay))
# using verbs as a function
df_filtered_verb <-arrange(df_filtered,desc(total_delay))

head(df_filtered,n=3)
## # A tibble: 3 × 7
##    year month   day dep_delay arr_delay carrier total_delay
##   <int> <int> <int>     <dbl>     <dbl> <chr>         <dbl>
## 1  2013     1     9      1301      1272 HA             2573
## 2  2013     6    15      1137      1127 MQ             2264
## 3  2013     1    10      1126      1109 MQ             2235
# Example:
# Arrange rows by arr_delay, followed by dep_delay
df_filtered <- df_filtered %>% arrange(arr_delay,dep_delay)
# using verbs as a function
df_filtered_verb <-arrange(df_filtered,arr_delay,dep_delay)

head(df_filtered,n=3)
## # A tibble: 3 × 7
##    year month   day dep_delay arr_delay carrier total_delay
##   <int> <int> <int>     <dbl>     <dbl> <chr>         <dbl>
## 1  2013     3     1         1       -65 DL              -64
## 2  2013     5     4         3       -63 UA              -60
## 3  2013    11    13         9       -63 DL              -54

Summarising

summarise() allows us to calculate descriptive statistics.

# summarise() or summarize() – Reduce Info to a Single Row
# to calculate summary statistics, such as the mean, sum, count, etc., 
# over one or more variables. 
# often pair with group_by() to calculate statistics by group.

# Example:
# Calculate average dep_delay and total_delay
# using pipe operator
df_summary <- df_filtered %>% 
  summarise(mean_dep_delay = mean(dep_delay), 
            mean_total_delay = mean(total_delay, na.rm = TRUE))
# na.rm = TRUE instructs R to ignore any missing values marked as NA when
# calculating

# using verbs as a function
df_summary_verb <- summarise(df_filtered,mean_dep_delay = mean(dep_delay), 
            mean_total_delay = mean(total_delay, na.rm = TRUE))

head(df_summary,n=3)
## # A tibble: 1 × 2
##   mean_dep_delay mean_total_delay
##            <dbl>            <dbl>
## 1           39.4             73.9
# fyi
# following two are the same commands, british or american spelling for summarise 
flights %>% filter(dest == 'ORD') %>% summarize(mean_dep_delay = mean(dep_delay)) # obtain number of flights with destination at ORD
## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##   mean_dep_delay
##            <dbl>
## 1             NA
flights %>% filter(dest == 'ORD') %>% summarise(mean_dep_delay = mean(dep_delay))
## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##   mean_dep_delay
##            <dbl>
## 1             NA

Additional examples using summarise()

# useful functions within summarise
# Mean (Average): Calculate the mean (average) value for a numeric column.
df%>% summarise(mean_value = mean(dep_delay,na.rm=TRUE))

# Sum: Calculate the sum of a numeric column.
df%>%summarise(total_dep_delay = sum(dep_delay,na.rm=TRUE))

# Median: Find the median value for a numeric column.
df%>% summarise(median_value = median(dep_delay,na.rm=TRUE))

# Standard Deviation: Calculate the standard deviation of a numeric column.
df%>%summarise(sd_value = sd(dep_delay,na.rm=TRUE))

# Variance: Calculate the variance of a numeric column.
df%>%summarise(sd_value = var(dep_delay,na.rm=TRUE))

# Minimum and Maximum: Find the minimum and maximum values of a column.
df%>%summarise(min_value = min(dep_delay,na.rm=TRUE),max_value = max(dep_delay,na.rm=TRUE))

# Quantiles: Calculate specific quantiles, like the 25th and 75th percentiles.
df%>%summarise(Q1 = quantile(dep_delay,0.25,na.rm=TRUE))

# Count: Count the number of records in each group.
df%>%summarise(count =n())

# there are other items that you can retrieve with summarise, 
# such as number of unique values, proportions,  etc.
# explore dplyr documentation for more info.

Grouping

group_by() is often paired with summarise() in order for us to aggregate data and calculate values for each group.

Message printed on console: summarise() has grouped output by columnname You can override using the .groups argument.

This message helps to make the user aware that a grouping was performed using columnname . However, the message does not have an impact on the final result. It is just a friendly warning message that can usually be ignored.

Also, when using multiple columns to group our data, dplyr drops the last group variable that was specified in the group_by function when printing the message.

# group_by() – Aggregate by Groups
# to split data into groups based on one or more variables. 
# After grouping, you can apply summary functions like summarise() 
# or mutate() to each group.

# Example:
# Group data by carrier and then 
# calculate average dep_delay and total_delay
# using pipe operator
df_group_summary <- df_filtered %>% group_by(carrier)%>%
  summarise(mean_dep_delay = mean(dep_delay), 
            mean_total_delay = mean(total_delay, na.rm = TRUE))

# using verbs as a function
# using dplyr functions as bested functions decreases 
# the readability of your code

df_group_summary_verb<-summarise(group_by(df_filtered,carrier),
                                 mean_dep_delay = mean(dep_delay), 
                                 mean_total_delay = mean(total_delay, 
                                                         na.rm = TRUE))
head(df_group_summary,n=3)

Joining

left_join() and right_join() are functions in dplyr which allows us to join data frames together. left_join(df1,df2 ) keeps all rows from df1 in the merged data frame while right_join(df1,df2) keeps all rows from df2 in the merged data frame.

# left_join() – Merge Data Objects
# merges two data frames (or tibbles) by a common column, 
# keeping all rows from the left data frame 
# and matching rows from the right data frame. 

# Example:
planes<-nycflights13::planes
df_left<-planes%>%select(tailnum,type,year)
df_right<-planes%>%select(tailnum,model,manufacturer)
# the common column needs to have unique values, else there will be complications
# using pipe operator
df_joined <- df_left %>% left_join(df_right, by = "tailnum")
# using verbs as a function
df_joined_verb <- left_join(df_left,df_right, by = "tailnum")

head(df_joined,n=3)
## # A tibble: 3 × 5
##   tailnum type                     year model     manufacturer    
##   <chr>   <chr>                   <int> <chr>     <chr>           
## 1 N10156  Fixed wing multi engine  2004 EMB-145XR EMBRAER         
## 2 N102UW  Fixed wing multi engine  1998 A320-214  AIRBUS INDUSTRIE
## 3 N103US  Fixed wing multi engine  1999 A320-214  AIRBUS INDUSTRIE

Additional functions in dplyr (optional)

# distinct() – Remove Duplicate Entries
# to return only unique rows or values, 
# removing duplicates based on one or more columns.

# Example:
# Find distinct carrier
# using pipe operator
df_distinct <- df_filtered %>% distinct(carrier)
# using verbs as a function
df_distinct_verb <- distinct(df_filtered,carrier)

head(df_distinct_verb,n=3)
## # A tibble: 3 × 1
##   carrier
##   <chr>  
## 1 DL     
## 2 UA     
## 3 HA
# Example:
# Find distinct day - month combinations
# using pipe operator
df_distinct_daymonths <- df_filtered %>% distinct(day,month)
# using verbs as a function
df_distinct_daymonths_verb <-distinct(df_filtered,day,month)
head(df_distinct_daymonths,n=3)
## # A tibble: 3 × 2
##     day month
##   <int> <int>
## 1     1     3
## 2     4     5
## 3    13    11
# ix) rename() – Rename Columns/Variables
# to rename one or more columns in a data frame.

# Example:
# Rename type as engine, tailnum as planeid in df_joined
# using pipe operator
df_renamed <- df_joined %>% rename(engine = type,planeid=tailnum)
# using verbs as a function
df_renamed_verb <- rename(df_joined,engine = type,planeid=tailnum)

# lubridate is a R package that makes dealing with time easier.
# We can use ymd() in lubridate to format dates. 

airportdailycounts <- flights %>% 
  filter(dest %in% c('ALB','BDL','BTV')) %>%
  group_by(year, month, day, dest) %>%
  summarise(numflights = n()) %>% mutate(date= ymd(paste(year, month, day, sep = "-")))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year', 'month', 'day'. You can override
## using the `.groups` argument.
# mutate generates a new column/variable
# here, we use mutate to generate a column called date, and using ymd() from lubridate

# to install and load ggplot2
if (!require('ggplot2')) install.packages('ggplot2'); library('ggplot2')
## Loading required package: ggplot2
## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 4.2.3
# plotting number of flights against date, and using separate colours for different destinations
ggplot(data = airportdailycounts, aes(x = date, y = numflights, colour = dest))+ geom_point()

# aes refers to axes. 
#geom_point() refers to shape of points. Nothing specified here. circles are default


# creating new variable for date 
airportmonthlycounts <- airportdailycounts %>% 
  mutate(FirstOfMonth = ymd(paste(year,"-", month, "-01", sep = "")))

ggplot(data=airportmonthlycounts,aes(x=FirstOfMonth, y = numflights, colour = dest)) + geom_point()

Task 4

Using dplyr verb select() - select a set of columns: the “name” and the “sleep_total” columns

  • select all the columns except a specific column, use the “-“ (subtraction) operator

  • select a range of columns by name, use the “:” (colon) operator

  • select all columns that start with the character string “sl”, use the function starts_with()

# 4. Using dplyr verb “select()”
# (a) select a set of columns: the “name” and the “sleep_total” columns

# method 1
df4a.1<-df%>% select(name,sleep_total)

# method 2
df4a.2<-select(df,name,sleep_total)

# (b) select all the columns except a specific column, use the “-“ (subtraction) operator

# method 1
df4b.1<-df%>% select(-sleep_total)

# method 2
df4b.2<-select(df,-sleep_total)

# (c) select a range of columns by name, use the “:” (colon) operator

# method 1
df4c.1<-df%>% select(genus:order)
df4c.2<-df%>% select(2:4)

# method 2
df4c.3<-select(df,genus:order)
df4c.4<-select(df,2:4)

# (d) select all columns that start with the character string “sl”, use the function starts_with()

# method 1
df4d.1<-df%>% select(starts_with("sl"))

# method 2
df4d.2<-select(df,starts_with("sl"))

Task 5

Using dplyr verb filter()

  • Filter the rows for mammals that sleep a total of more than 16 hours.

  • Filter the rows for mammals that sleep a total of more than 16 hours and have a body weight of greater than 1 kilogram.

  • Filter the rows for mammals with order as “Perissodactyla” and “Primates”

# a) Filter the rows for mammals that sleep a total of more than 16 hours.

df5a.1<-df%>% filter(sleep_total>16)

Task 7

Using arrange()

  • Select three columns from sleepdata, arrange the rows by the order and then arrange the rows by sleep_total. Finally filter the rows for mammals that sleep for 16 or more hours

  • Change the order of sleep_total column to a descending order using the function desc() in the step above.

# (a) Select three columns from sleepdata, arrange the rows by the order and 
# then arrange the rows by sleep_total. 
# Finally filter the rows for mammals that sleep for 16 or more hours

# Method 1
df7a.1<-df%>%arrange(order,sleep_total)%>%filter(sleep_total>16)%>%select(name,order,sleep_total)

# Method 2
df7a.2<-select(filter(arrange(df,order,sleep_total),sleep_total>16),name,order,sleep_total)

# (b) Change the order of sleep_total column to a descending order using 
# the function desc() in the step above.

# Method 1
df7b.1<-df%>%arrange(order,desc(sleep_total))%>%filter(sleep_total>16)%>%select(name,order,sleep_total)

# Method 2
df7b.2<-select(filter(arrange(df,order,desc(sleep_total)),sleep_total>16),name,order,sleep_total)
